{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606689"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:15:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:15:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15929"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15929"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.24,0.36,0.16,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8620"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72837"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8620"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15929"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58307"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8673"},{"type":"tags","id":"8675"},{"type":"tags","id":"8685"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20649"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72837"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryological development, three pairs of kidneys develop in a cranial to caudal sequence: the pronephros, mesonephros, and metanephros. Each serves different developmental roles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mesonephros?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Develops from the metanephric blastema","Develops after the pronephros degenerates at week 16","Develops during week four and degenerates by week 12 in females","Forms the female reproductive tract","Persists throughout life as the definitive kidney"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emesonephros develops during week four of embryological development and degenerates by week 12 in females\u003C/strong\u003E. It serves as a temporary excretory organ during early embryological development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn males, while the mesonephros degenerates, its duct (the mesonephric or Wolffian duct) persists and gives rise to male reproductive structures including the epididymis, vas deferens, and seminal vesicles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelops from the metanephric blastema\u003C/strong\u003E - The mesonephros develops from intermediate mesoderm, not the metanephric blastema\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelops after the pronephros degenerates at week 16\u003C/strong\u003E - The pronephros degenerates much earlier, around week 3.5\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms the female reproductive tract\u003C/strong\u003E - The paramesonephric (M\u00fcllerian) duct forms female reproductive structures, not the mesonephros\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPersists throughout life as the definitive kidney\u003C/strong\u003E - The metanephros becomes the definitive kidney, while the mesonephros is temporary\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The mesonephros develops during week four of embryological development and degenerates by week 12 in females.","The mesonephric (Wolffian) duct gives rise to male reproductive structures including the epididymis, vas deferens, and seminal vesicles.","The mesonephros functions temporarily as an excretory organ in the embryo before the metanephros develops."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Rehman S, Ahmed D. Embryology, Kidney, Bladder, and Ureter. In: StatPearls [Online].  [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK547747/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58307"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15929"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58307"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T09:41:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T09:42:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8620"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72837"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"item